# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ba-game
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The **12th man** or **12th player** is a collective term for fans of sports teams in many eleven-a-side games, in particular association football.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] As most football leagues allow a maximum of eleven players per team on the playing field at a time, referring to a team's fans as the 12th man implies that they have a potentially helpful and significant role in the game.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The presence of fans can have a notable impact on teams' performance, an element in the home advantage.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Namely, the home team fans would vocally support and urge on their team to win the game.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Thus, these fans will often create loud sounds or chant in the hope of encouraging their team, or of distracting, demoralizing, or confusing the opposing team while they have possession of the ball, or to persuade a referee to make a favorable decision for the team.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Noises are made by shouting, singing, whistling, stomping, clapping, and various other techniques.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In Canadian football, 12 players from each team are usually on the field at one time and the term **13th man** is often used to refer to fans.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Similarly, in Australian rules football, 18 players are on the field, and the fans are often referred to as the **19th man**.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] However, in basketball, where five players are on the court, the term *Sixth man* generally refers to an energetic substitute player.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Similarly, in rugby sevens, with seven players from each team on the field, "Eighth man" is not used to refer to fans as the term refers to the eighth forward in rugby union.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The term *Twelfth Man* has a specifically different meaning in cricket, referring instead to the nominated first substitute player who fields when a member of the fielding side is injured during play.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The first recorded use of the term "twelfth man" was a magazine published by the University of Minnesota in September 1900, that referred to "the mysterious influence of the twelfth man on the team, the rooter".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Later, in the November 1912 edition of *The Iowa Alumnus*, an alumni publication of the University of Iowa (then known as State University of Iowa), E.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] McGowan described the 1903 game between Iowa and the University of Illinois.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The 1922 Dixie Classic served as the setting for an event later referred to as "The story of the 12th Man".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] This football game featured the top-ranked Centre College and The Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas (later known as Texas A&M).
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Bible realized that one more injury would leave him without another backfield player to send into the game.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] King Gill, a sophomore basketball player, down from the stands to stand ready as a substitute.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Gill was ready in uniform on the sidelines if his team needed him.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Individuals have occasionally been labeled by local media as the "Twelfth Man" of their team.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Adamson, Principal of Oak Cliff (Dallas) High School was called the "Twelfth Man" of the school's American football team by a local reporter due to the rousing pre-game speeches he would give to the players.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Likewise, sometimes, fans of both teams in an annual contest have been described as the 12th man.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The Bears currently use the phrase "4th Phase" (with the first three phases being offense, defense, and special teams), and the Seahawks currently use the phrase "The 12s".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Many high schools in the United States incorporate 12th man language into their booster, supporter, or rooter clubs.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Examples of such "12th Man Clubs" include the Dana Hills Dolphins, Washington Panthers, Richwood Knights, Diamond Bar Brahmas, Fairfield Falcons, and Brentwood Bruins.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The Campbellsville University Tigers of the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics also have a 12th Man Club.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] On December 12, 1992, (12/12/1992) the Buffalo Bills of the National Football League honored their 12th Man as the seventh inductee into the Buffalo Bills Wall of Fame, located inside Highmark Stadium.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Their fans were inducted because of their loyal support during the team's early '90s Super Bowl runs, which coincided with quarterback Jim Kelly and his wearing of #12.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In 2008, the Bills renamed their "12th Man Walk of Fame" as "Tim Russert Plaza", in honor of the recently deceased Buffalo native and lifelong fan.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The team continues to refer to its fans as the "12th Man", with their independent, international fan clubs known as "Bills Backers Chapters".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The Bills have a licensing agreement with Texas A&M over the use of the "12th Man" term.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] From 2007 to 2016, fans of the Indianapolis Colts of the NFL were known as the 12th Man.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The Colts created a Ring of Honor on September 23, 1996, after playing 13 seasons in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In 2007, the Colts inducted their 12th Man as the sixth entrant into the team's Ring of Honor, then located on the interior facade of the RCA Dome.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The Ring of Honor currently encircles Lucas Oil Stadium, the team's home venue.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The organization also designates a "12th Man Fan of the Game".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M announced the filing of a lawsuit against the Colts based on the team's usage of the term.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] On February 17, 2016, the lawsuit was settled with the Colts agreeing to remove the phrase from their Ring of Honor and to immediately cease all other uses of the trademarked phrase.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The Seattle Seahawks retired the number 12 jersey on December 15, 1984, in honor of their fans.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In 2003, the Seahawks installed a giant flagpole in the south end zone of what is now Lumen Field, and began a tradition of raising a giant flag with the number 12 on it in honor of the fans, one of whom is Sam Adkins, the former Seahawks quarterback who did wear the number 12.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Usually, a local celebrity or a season ticket holder raises the flag during pregame ceremonies.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In recent years, 12th Man flags have been seen all over Seattle whenever the Seahawks make the playoffs, including atop the Space Needle.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In 2014, Boeing painted a Boeing 747-8 freighter aircraft with a special Seahawks livery, with the number 12 on the tail, and they later flew it over eastern Washington in a flight path spelling the number 12.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] When the Seahawks took the field for Super Bowl XLVIII, they were led by LB Heath Farwell carrying the team's 12th Man flag per team tradition.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In May 2016, mountaineer David Liaño González displayed a 12th Man flag at the summit of Mount Everest.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] As per an agreement struck between the Seahawks and Texas A&M in 2016, the Seahawks have virtually ceased from referring to their fans as the "12th Man", and instead are using the term "12s" or the 12 Fan.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The first known instance of Texas A&M referring to its fanbase as the "12th Man" is contained on page 17 of the November 25, 1921, edition of *The Battalion*, the Texas A&M campus newspaper.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] King Gill left the stands in 1922; the entire student body stood throughout the game to symbolize their "readiness, desire, and enthusiasm" to take the field if needed.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Football coach Jackie Sherrill created the "12th Man Kick-Off Team" in the 1980s, composed of non-athletic scholarship students who tried out for the team.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Coach Sherrill has written a book entitled "No Experience Required" which details this team and the tradition.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] These students were placed on the roster for the sole purpose of kickoffs.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The squad was nicknamed "the suicide squad".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] These students often had little regard for their safety and were determined to make a tackle at any cost.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The 12th Man Kick-Off Team was extremely successful and eventually held opponents to one of the lowest yards-per-return average in the league during kickoffs.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Slocum changed the team to allow only one representative of the 12th Man on the kickoff team who wears uniform number 12.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The player is chosen based on the level of determination and hard work shown in practices.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Under Dennis Franchione, the 12th Man Kick-Off Team, composed of walk-ons, was brought back, though used only rarely when the team was up by quite a few points.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] On June 30, 2014, Texas A&M bought the domain name 12thman.com, which then became its official athletics website.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In 1986, the Washington Redskins (now known as the Washington Commanders) released a video entitled "Thanks to the 12th Man".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The term "12th man" is commonly used in football to refer to the fans and occasionally the manager.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] A notable club famous for the twelfth man reference comes from Aston Villa, referring to the Holte End stand at Villa Park.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Large European teams such as Bayern Munich, Malmö FF, Hammarby IF, Helsingborgs IF, Werder Bremen, Aberdeen, Rangers, Lazio, PSV, Feyenoord, Ferencvárosi TC, FC Red Star, Fenerbahçe S.K., and Sporting CP have officially retired the number 12 to the fans.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Stockport County fans are registered as official members of their squad with the number 12.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Portsmouth F.C. has also retired its number 12 shirt, and lists the club's supporters, "Pompey Fans", as player number 12 on the squad list printed in home match programmes, while Plymouth Argyle have theirs registered to the *Green Army* (the nickname for their fans).
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] On Hammarby IF's, Helsingborgs IF, Malmö FF, Feyenoord and Werder Bremen's home games, the stadium speaker announces number 12 as "the fans" during team lineup announcements.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Dynamo Dresden in Germany also keeps number 12 for their fans, as well as the official team anthem being "We are the 12th man".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Aberdeen F.C. supporters commonly display a large banner in the shape of a football shirt with the text "Red Army 12" in place of a player's name and number.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The fans of the Northern Ireland national football team and Derry City are referred to as the 12th man as well.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In the League of Ireland, Shamrock Rovers F.C. retired the number 12 jersey in recognition of the fans who took over the club in 2005.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Cork City F.C., Clube Atlético Mineiro and Clube de Regatas do Flamengo also retired the number 12 for the fans.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The most vociferous fans of Boca Juniors in Argentina are known as the "Jugador Numero 12" (Spanish for "Player Number 12") or simply "La Doce" ("The 12").
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Lecce, an Italian team currently playing in Serie B, retired the number 12 to the fans, which was handed to them by the former captain Cristian Ledesma.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] They symbolically represent a 12th Man in the field.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In the beginning of 2009–2010 season, Happy Valley AA introduced the club's mascot, a panda, on squad list as the fan club captain wearing the number 12 jersey.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] As of the end of the 2011–2012 season, Rangers F.C announced that the number 12 jersey would be retired in honour of the fans support throughout a period of financial difficulty.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In American football, the sideline is sometimes also referred to as the "12th man" or "12th defender": since a player is considered down when he steps out of bounds, the sideline effectively acts as an extra defender.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] This usage is less common than the one referring to the fans.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In most sports the term can also be construed to mean the referee, implying that the match official favours one team and is not impartial.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The effects of the "12th man" vary widely, but can be put in two categories.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The first is simply psychological, the effect of showing the home team that they are appreciated, and showing the away team that they are somewhat unwelcome.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The second directly relates to the deafening effects of a loud crowd.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In Association football, the crowd can be very passionate and often sing throughout the whole match.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Some occasions where the crowd noise is extra loud can be before kickoff; during the buildup to and scoring of a goal; when encouraging the team to come back from defeat; to discourage an opposition penalty taker; or to harass a referee giving a free kick to the opposition team.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In American football, fans are most incited by physical play, especially good plays made by the defense.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Additionally, the home team can derive energy from the loud noise of their fans; former American football players have described the feeling of their adrenaline pumping after hearing the fans yell, which is "like you have a reserve energy tank".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The noise of the crowd can have a significant impact on the players on the field.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In American football, an extremely loud crowd can prevent the offensive linemen from hearing the snap count.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] This can have the effect of making the player slower to react when the ball is snapped, and his eventual response may be weaker than normal because each play is begun "with some indecision and doubt".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The noise can also prevent players from hearing audibles and can make it difficult for the team's offense to coordinate plays in the huddle.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The effect of the noise can often be measured in mistakes, such as false start penalties.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Coaches can take steps to minimize the effect of the crowd noise on their teams.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Some American football teams bring large speakers to their practice fields and broadcast loud noises such as jet engines to prepare their teams for the anticipated noise level.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Crowd noise tends to diminish after a long lull in play, such as a pause for instant replay.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Former NFL player Brian Baldinger speculates that some coaches draw out reviews as part of a coaching strategy to quiet the crowd for their next play.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] A researcher from Harvard University discovered in a study that some association football referees appeared to be impacted by crowd noise.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] His studies revealed that a home team acquired an additional 0.1 goal advantage for every 10,000 fans in the stadium.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Delia Smith, Norwich City's joint major shareholder, received some attention when she took to the pitch during a half time interval, with a microphone in hand and Sky TV cameras in tow, to tell fans the side "need their twelfth man".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Norwich City lost the game in the final seconds, but Smith's passion worked to increase the affection the fans held for her.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The current naturally loudest football stadium is Nef Stadium in Istanbul home of Galatasaray S.K.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] As a prepared attempt, the current world record for crowd noise at an athletic event was set on September 29, 2014, when the Kansas City Chiefs hosted the New England Patriots.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Noise during that event reached a high of 142.2 decibels during a timeout.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Texas A&M University applied on December 26, 1989, for trademark U.S.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The United States Patent and Trademark Office issued the "trademark registration" September 4, 1990, to Texas A&M.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Four additional Trademark claims related to the "12th Man" term were also filed and granted at later dates by Texas A&M University (See U.S.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] 74560726, 76671314, 85977835 and 85851199), the first three of which have achieved Incontestable Status as a result of its section 15 affidavit with the Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] According to former Texas A&M Athletic Director Bill Byrne, he contacted the Chicago Bears and Buffalo Bills about halting their "12th Man" themes.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Byrne stated that, "they responded quickly with our requests to stop using our Twelfth Man trademark".
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Texas A&M sent requests to stop using the phrase to the Seattle Seahawks in both 2004 and 2005.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The Seahawks did not respond to the requests.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In January 2006, Texas A&M filed a trademark infringement lawsuit against the Seattle Seahawks and in May 2006, the dispute was settled out of court.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] Neither side admitted any fault or liability.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In the agreement, the Seahawks licensed the phrase in exchange for $100,000, along with public acknowledgement as to Texas A&M's ownership rights of the phrase, and an additional annual fee.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The compensation amounted to $5,000 per year.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The agreement, which expired in 2016, limited the Seahawks' usage to seven western states and forbid them from selling any "12th Man" merchandise.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In August 2015, the Seahawks shifted towards calling their fans the "12s", and replaced their "Home of the 12th Man" stadium sign with a new "Home of the 12s" sign.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M filed suit against the Indianapolis Colts after repeated cease and desist requests were ignored by the NFL team.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] In August 2016, the Seahawks agreed to a new five-year trademark licensing agreement with Texas A&M.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] As part of the agreement, the Seahawks agreed to pay Texas A&M $140,000 for limited rights to use the trademarked term.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] This agreement, like the previous agreement, prohibits the Seahawks from using the "12th Man" term on any merchandise.
[src:ba-game/12th-man-football] The new agreement, however, also prohibits Seattle from using the term on social media, nor are they allowed to use the term on any signage within their stadium, including their Ring of Honor.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:ba-game/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 1872 association football match between the national teams of Scotland and England is officially recognised by FIFA as the first international.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It took place on 30 November 1872 at Hamilton Crescent, the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground in Partick, Glasgow.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was watched by 4,000 spectators and finished as a 0–0 draw.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Following public challenges issued in Glasgow and Edinburgh newspapers by The Football Association (FA) secretary Charles Alcock, the first encounter of five matches between teams representing England and Scotland took place in London on 5 March 1870 at The Oval, resulting in a 1–1 draw.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The second match was played on 19 November 1870, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] This was followed by matches on 25 February 1871, England 1–1 Scotland; 18 November 1871, England 2–1 Scotland; and 24 February 1872, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Most players selected for the Scottish side in these early "internationals" were from the London area, although players based in Scotland were also invited.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The only player affiliated to a Scottish club was Robert Smith of Queen's Park, Glasgow, who played in the November 1870 match and both of the 1871 games.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Robert Smith and James Smith (both of the Queen's Park club) were listed publicly for the February 1872 game, but neither played in the match.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] After the 1870 matches, there was resentment in Scotland that their team did not contain more players based in Scotland.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Alcock then proceeded to offer another challenge with a Scottish team drawn from Scotland and proposed the north of England as a venue.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] He appeared to be particularly concerned about the number of players in Scottish football teams at the time, adding: "More than eleven we do not care to play as it is with greater numbers it is our opinion the game becomes less scientific and more a trial of charging and brute force ...
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Charles W Alcock, Hon Sec of Football Association and Captain of English Eleven".
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] One reason for the absence of a formal response to Alcock's challenge may have been different football codes being followed in Scotland at the time.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] A written reply to Alcock's letter above states: "Mr Alcock's challenge to meet a Scotch eleven on the borders sounds very well and is doubtless well meant.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] But it may not be generally well known that Mr Alcock is a very leading supporter of what is called the 'association game' ... devotees of the 'association' rules will find no foemen worthy of their steel in Scotland".
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Despite this the FA were hoping to play in Scotland as early as February 1872.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In 1872, Queen's Park, as Scotland's leading club, took up Alcock's challenge, despite there being no Scottish Football Association to sanction it.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In the FA's minutes of 3 October 1872 it was noted "In order to further the interests of the Association in Scotland, it was decided that during the current season, a team should be sent to Glasgow to play a match v Scotland".
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was arranged for 30 November (St Andrew's Day), and the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground at Hamilton Crescent in Partick was selected as the venue.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] All eleven Scottish players were members of the Queen's Park, the leading Scottish club at this time, although three players were also members of other clubs; William Ker of Granville F.C. and the Smith brothers of South Norwood F.C.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland had hoped to obtain the services of Arthur Kinnaird of The Wanderers and Henry Renny-Tailyour of Royal Engineers but both were unavailable.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The teams for this match were gathered together "with some difficulty, each side losing some of their best men almost at the last moment".
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scottish side was selected by goalkeeper and captain Robert Gardner.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English side was selected by Charles Alcock and contained players from nine clubs; Alcock himself was unable to play due to injury.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match, initially scheduled for 2pm, was delayed for 20 minutes.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 4,000 spectators paid an entry fee of a shilling, the same amount charged at the 1872 FA Cup Final.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English wore caps, while the Scots wore red cowls.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match itself illustrated the advantage gained by the Queen's Park players "through knowing each others' play" as all came from the same club.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] There is no evidence in the article that the author attended the match, as the reader is clearly pointed to match descriptions in "sporting journals".
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It is also of note that the 5 March 1872 match between Wanderers and Queen's Park contains no evidence of ball passing.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] At half-time, both teams rotated the goalkeeping duties among their players: England from Robert Barker to William Maynard, and Scotland from Gardner to Robert Smith.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] On a pitch that was heavy due to the continuous rain over the previous three days, the smaller and lighter Scottish side pushed their English counterparts hard.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots had a goal disallowed in the first half after the umpires decided that the ball had cleared the tape that was used to represent the crossbar.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The latter part of the match saw the Scots defence under pressure by the heavier English forwards.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots played two full backs, two half backs and six forwards.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English played only one full back, one half back and eight forwards.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Since three defenders were required for a ball played to be onside, the English system was virtually a ready-made offside trap.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland came closest to winning the match when, in the closing stages, a Robert Leckie shot landed on top of the tape.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Though the match finished goalless, the quality of play was widely praised.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] "It was allowed to be the best game ever seen in Scotland" wrote the *Aberdeen Journal*.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The reports of the match that were published in the newspapers reveal further details of the 1872 Laws of the Game.
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland won a defensive corner kick after England's attackers kicked the ball over the goal-line (a feature borrowed from Sheffield Rules but discarded in 1873).
[src:ba-game/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The throw-in was awarded to the first team to touch the ball down after it went out of play (this too would be changed in 1873); and there was a break for half-time only because no goals had been scored in the first half.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] 3v3 is a faster paced and higher scoring game than traditional full-sided soccer.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] The speed of the attack, the use of triangulation, and the strategies bring aspects of hockey into the game.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] The quick shift from one end of the field to the other after a goal is scored, or upon loss of possession is reminiscent of basketball.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] It requires the blending of individual skills with teamwork.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] The sport's popularity is attributed to every member of the team getting equal playing time, and roughly equal touches on the ball.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] All players on the field are a part of the play.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] Because of the speed of the game, and the fact that players are constantly in motion, there are frequent substitutions.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] A typical player may be rotated on six times or more in one game.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] There are no permanently assigned positions as there are in full-sided soccer, giving each team member equal status and equal importance.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] This helps to develop individual skills.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] Nike helped to popularize the sport with its international Joga3 Joga Bonito Tour in 2006, in which teams qualified at local events around the World, culminating in a 3v3 World Cup played in Brazil.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] In 2023, the popularity of 3v3 soccer was on the rise in countries such as Serbia and Australia.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] Since the beginning of 2023, many tournaments have emerged for players across various age groups.
[src:ba-game/3v3-soccer] These tournaments include Kick It 3v3 Soccer and 3v3 Live Soccer Tour.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:ba-game/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:ba-game/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:ba-game/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:ba-game/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:ba-game/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:ba-game/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:ba-game/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:ba-game/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:ba-game/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:ba-game/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:ba-game/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:ba-game/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:ba-game/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:ba-game/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:ba-game/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:ba-game/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:ba-game/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:ba-game/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:ba-game/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] The **ASEAN All-Stars** is a football team founded by the ASEAN Football Federation in 2014.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] The team is made up of Southeast Asia internationals and selected players from the regional leagues.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] The ASEAN Football Federation (AFF) announced in April 2014 that a friendly will be held involving the Indonesian national team and an ASEAN All-Stars team.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] It was meant as a charity event in aid of victims of Typhoon Haiyan which affected the Philippines in 2013.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] Victims of the eruption of Mount Kelud and Mount Sinabung in Indonesia were also reportedly beneficiaries as well.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] The ASEAN team was coached by Malaysian coach K.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] Thai coach Piyapong Pue-on was supposed to lead the team but was replaced by Rajagopal.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] Radojko Avramović, Winfried Schäfer, and Michael Weiß were also ASEAN head coach candidates.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] The charity match was held at the Gelora Bung Karno Stadium on 11 May 2014.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] English Premier League club Manchester United lost 0–1 against ASEAN All-Stars team on 28 May 2025 at the Bukit Jalil National Stadium in front of a crowd of 72,550.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] Myanmar player Maung Maung Lwin scored the sole goal of the match in the 71st minute.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] The friendly was billed as the Maybank Challenge Cup and the proceeds was pledged to go to the charity organisation, Al-Sultan Abdullah Foundation (YASA).
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] The match was organised by ProEvents International.
[src:ba-game/asean-all-stars] South Korean Kim Sang-sik was the team's head coach, while their captain was Ezequiel Agüero of Malaysia.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] The **Ba' Game** is a version of medieval football played in Scotland, primarily in Orkney and the Scottish Borders, around Christmas and New Year.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] Ba' is essentially mob football, or village football, where two parts of a town have to get a ball to goals on their respective sides.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] The two sides are called the Uppies or the Doonies, depending on which part of town they were born, or otherwise owe allegiance to.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] The ball must be man handled, and play often takes the form of a moving scrum.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] The game moves through the town, at times going up alleyways, into yards and through streets.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] Shops and houses board up their windows to prevent damage.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] Unlike traditional mob football, people are generally not hurt from play.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] It is thought that at one time there may have been more than 200 similar games across the UK, with around 15 still being played today.
[src:ba-game/ba-game] The laddies game in Jedburgh in 2020; on the left they reach for the ball and the uppies then take it to the right.
